<HEAD>Thousands Surge Through as Berlin Wall Opens at Brandenburg Gate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to ADD quotes from revelers. Pickup 8th pvs,
`The crowd...' Delete 19th graf pvs, `Others held...' to remove reference
to Ceausescu.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BER19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of jubilant <ORGANIZATION>Berliners</ORGANIZATION> surged
through new openings in the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall at the <LOCATION>Brandenburg Gate</LOCATION>
<DATE>today</DATE> for the first time in 28 years.
   The celebrants braved an intermittent rain as they filled the
square in front of the towering symbol of the postwar division of
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> that is becoming a monument to the rapprochement of <LOCATION>East
Germany</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>.
   East German Premier <PERSON>Hans Modrow</PERSON> met <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> Chancellor
<PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON> at the border for the <TIME>3 p.m.</TIME> (<TIME>9 a.m. EST</TIME>) ceremony,
then they walked together into <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>. They were nearly
mobbed by the crowd as they walked to a platform in front of the
gate to address the exulting Berliners.
   Kohl called the occasion ``a fantastic thing.''
   Thousands drenched by the rain uncorked champagne and danced
atop the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall, the once impregnable concrete barrier that is
quickly crumbling.
   The opening was televised live in both countries. ``This is
where the heart of <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> pounds,'' said a commentator for <LOCATION>West
Germany</LOCATION>'s ZDF network.
   Two banners were unfurled near the new crossings to protest the
killings of demonstrators in <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>.
   ``The last time I was here was as a kid when I used to play on
this very spot. I never thought I'd come here again, it's really
wonderful,'' said <PERSON>Peter Rebachmann</PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>.
   ``What a beautiful Christmas present. I am so elated that I can
experience this,'' said a middle-aged woman.
   The crowd cheered and set off firecrackers when East German
workers started dismantling the wall <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>. The workers
used a crane to remove the rounded top of the wall.
   ``This is an experience that will go down in history. The gate
was a symbol of division of <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON>Jozef Polak</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>West
Berlin</LOCATION> mechanic.
   More than 10,000 people had jammed the western side for the two
sections of the wall to fall down. Some climbed on trees to get a
better view. More people kept arriving throughout the <TIME>night</TIME>.
   A loud cheer sounded through the <TIME>night</TIME> air as the East German
crane lifted a 3{-foot-wide segment of the concrete to make the
first hole in that part of the wall shortly after <TIME>midnight</TIME>.
   The two new crossing points are 15 feet wide each. One is for
Westerners going into <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>, the other for East Germans going
to <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION>.
   Although more than 20 border crossings have been made at the
wall since <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> opened its borders to the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION> on <DATE>Nov. 9</DATE>,
the <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION> has the most symbolic meaning for <ORGANIZATION>Berliners</ORGANIZATION>.
   The 200-year-old gate, <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>'s most famous landmark, remained
on the eastern side when <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>'s Communist authorities built
the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall in <DATE>1961</DATE>.
   Graffiti on the western side at one of the segments to be
removed said, ``One day every wall must fall down.''
   <PERSON>Friedhelm Brinkman</PERSON>, a salesman from <LOCATION>Dortmund</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, said
he drove 360 miles to see the event.
   ``This was the central place in <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> where everything happened
(before the war). I always thought this place would be opened again
and that's why I came tonight,'' he said <DATE>late Thursday</DATE>.
   Some people in the crowd shouted, ``<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>United
Fatherland</ORGANIZATION>,'' _ the rallying call of East German supporters of
German unification.
   
   The crowd was kept well away from the wall by barricades and
cordons of <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> police to prevent them from possibly trying
to cross the wall.
   After <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>'s dramatic opening of the borders, thousands
of people danced on the section of the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall at <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg
Gate</ORGANIZATION>.
   Crowds pulled down one segment of the wall in unforgettable
scenes seen on television worldwide. Thousands of people had waited
in vain for the gate to be opened in the first few days after the
<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall started crumbling down in the wake of <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>'s
peaceful revolution.
   Kohl and <PERSON>Modrow</PERSON> announced the agreement to open the two
crossings when <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> visited <LOCATION>Dresden</LOCATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   The gate, the size of a five-story building on top of which is a
bronze chariot with the goddess <PERSON>Victoria</PERSON>, was the backdrop for
<PERSON>Hitler</PERSON>'s rise to power and his last stand. It was also where East
German workers began a <DATE>1953</DATE> uprising that was crushed by Soviet
tanks.
   In <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>, the famous Unter den <PERSON>Linden</PERSON> boulevard ends at
the gate. On the Western side, the sprawling avenue that leads to
the gate was renamed <DATE>June 17</DATE> Street, after the date of the uprising.
   Nazi brown shirts staged a triumphant torch parade through the
gate when <PERSON>Adolf Hitler</PERSON> was named chancellor on <DATE>Jan. 30, 1933</DATE>.
   In the final days of World War II, the six-column sandstone gate
was heavily damaged as Soviet tanks closed in on Hitler's bunker in
the chancellory. It marked the border between the Soviet and
British sectors when the victorious allies divided conquered <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>
into four sectors.
</TEXT>
