<HEAD>200-Year-Old Gate Again a Stage for History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle-scarred sandstone columns of the
<ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION>, which were the backdrop for Hitler's last stand
and a workers' uprising against Communism in <DATE>1953</DATE>, once again tower
over the stage of history.
   The 200-year-old gate, <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>'s most famous landmark, has stood
as the symbol of German division for 28 years.
   With the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall quickly crumbling, the gate is being called
the symbol of German unity. It also has been the backdrop for much
of the television coverage beamed around the world in the past week
of fast-moving developments.
   <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> has said it is considering opening a <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall
border crossing at the <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION>. There was wide speculation
in <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> that an opening would be knocked through the wall
<DATE>Thursday</DATE>, although there was no official confirmation.
   The gate _ the size of a five-story building _ remained on the
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> side when the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall was built in <DATE>1961</DATE>. The famous
Unten den <PERSON>Linden</PERSON> boulevard ends at the gate.
   On the Western side, the sprawling avenue that leads to the gate
was renamed <DATE>June 17</DATE> Street, after the date of the workers' uprising
in <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION> in <DATE>1953</DATE> that was bloodily crushed by Soviet tanks.
   East <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> workers, angered by the nationalization and
collectivization policies of the Communist government, began their
street demonstrations at the <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION> and tore down the red
flag from the top of the gate.
   In the closing days of World War II, Soviet tanks rumbled by the
gate as they closed in on <PERSON>Adolf Hitler</PERSON>'s bunker in the chancellery.
Only a few hundred yards away was the heart of Hitler's government
in a small complex on <LOCATION>Wilhelmstrasse</LOCATION>, which also served as the seat
of the imperial government. The Reichstag also is not far away.
   The Brandenburg Gate also marked <PERSON>Hitler</PERSON>'s rise to power. Nazi
brown shirts staged a triumphant torch parade through the gate when
<PERSON>Hitler</PERSON> was named chancellor on <DATE>Jan. 30, 1933</DATE>.
   Built from <DATE>1788</DATE> to <DATE>1791</DATE> by <PERSON>Carl Gotthard Langhans</PERSON>, the
six-column gate was commissioned by Prussian King <PERSON>Frederick Wilhelm
II</PERSON>. When it was built, it opened the road to the region of
<LOCATION>Brandenburg</LOCATION>, getting its name.
   The gate was modeled after the <LOCATION>Acropolis</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION> to reflect
the king's intention to make <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> a city of learning and arts.
   On top of the gate is a bronze chariot with the goddess
<PERSON>Victoria</PERSON>. It was hauled away to <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> when <PERSON>Napoleon</PERSON> defeated the
Prussians at <ORGANIZATION>Jena</ORGANIZATION> and Auerstadt on <DATE>Oct. 27, 1806</DATE>. He marched into
<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> through the <LOCATION>Brandenburg Gate</LOCATION>.
   The chariot was brought back to <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> after <PERSON>Napoleon</PERSON>'s defeat
in <DATE>1814</DATE>. After the Franco-German war in 1870-71, the victorious
Prussians made a triumphal return to <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>, the new imperial
capital, again through the <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION>.
   The gate was heavily damaged in the last days of World War II
and marked the border between the Soviet and British sectors of
conquered <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>.
   It was restored between <DATE>1956</DATE> and <DATE>1958</DATE>. The chariot was repaired
and paid for by <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> under Mayor <PERSON>Willy Brandt</PERSON>, but <LOCATION>East
Berlin</LOCATION> authorities removed the Prussian eagle and the iron cross
from <LOCATION>Victoria</LOCATION>'s staff before mounting it again.
   In <DATE>1963</DATE>, Communist soldiers dropped huge red drapes over the
gate to prevent President <PERSON>John F. Kennedy</PERSON> from looking into <LOCATION>East
Berlin</LOCATION> when he visited <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> and delivered his ``Ich bin ein
Berliner'' speech.
   The gate, the last of the 20 gates to <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> still standing, is
66 feet high, 215 feet wide and 36 feet deep.
</TEXT>
