<HEAD>East Germans to Allow Unchecked Travel Through Brandenburg Gate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> will tear down a 600-foot
section of the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall near the Brandenburg Gate and allow
completely unhindered passage between the two sides of the city
there, West German television said.
   Since <DATE>November</DATE>, the East Germans have created numerous passage
points through the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall but have retained nominal checks of
passports or identity cards.
   The section at the <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION> will be the first section
without any official controls.
   ``The <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall at the <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION> will be torn down,''
the <ORGANIZATION>ZDF</ORGANIZATION> television network said <DATE>Friday</DATE>. ``East German border troops
will start the work on <DATE>Monday</DATE>.''
   ``There will then be unhindered passage between East and West
from the <LOCATION>Reichstag</LOCATION> to the <LOCATION>Brandenburg Gate</LOCATION>. There will not be a
fence there as originally planned.''
   The wall, for years a symbol of the division of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, was
built in <DATE>1961</DATE> to prevent East German laborers from leaving. A
popular uprising in <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> <DATE>last fall</DATE> toppled the hard-line
leadership and forced the opening of the wall in <DATE>November</DATE>.
</TEXT>
