<HEAD>Mayors of Divided City Meet at Berlin Wall's Newest Breach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayors of East and <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> shook hands
<DATE>Sunday</DATE> at a new <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall crossing point in a historic meeting
symbolizing the crumbling of the Cold War relic that divided the
city since <DATE>1961</DATE>.
   Their meeting came after more than 1 million East Germans poured
into <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, taking advantage of their
government's opening of Western borders. The vast majority intended
to make a brief visit and then return to the <LOCATION>East</LOCATION>.
   On <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON>Walter Momper</PERSON> and his <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>
counterpart, <PERSON>Erhard Krack</PERSON>, met at the <LOCATION>Potsdamer Platz</LOCATION>, a bleak,
virtual no-man's land bisected by the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall.
   Hours before their morning session, East German workers drilled
a hole through the wall with jackhammers at <LOCATION>Potsdamer Platz</LOCATION>,
creating the third new border crossing point since <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>'s
Communist leaders announced the end of travel restrictions late
last week.
   Momper and <PERSON>Krack</PERSON> later left the area for breakfast and talks in
a <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> hotel.
   The new freedom to travel and other reforms in <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> have
touched off a wave of enthusiam about the possibility of reuniting
the two German states divided at the end of World War II.
   However, East German Communist leader <PERSON>Egon Krenz</PERSON> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE>
dismissed such talk.
   The new wave of visitors to <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> on
<DATE>Sunday</DATE> was expected to exceed <DATE>Saturday</DATE>'s estimated 1.3 million
visitors, almost <PERCENT>8 percent</PERCENT> of East German's 16.6 million population.
   Most of <DATE>Saturday</DATE>'s exuberant visitors returned home overnight,
West German border police said.
   A core of East German and <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> revelers kept a joyful
vigil in front of the <LOCATION>Brandenburg Gate</LOCATION> on the western side of the
<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall.
   However, <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> riot police vans lined up in front of the
wall at the <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION> <DATE>early Sunday</DATE> to try to fend off
revelers who lit torches and candles in memory of East Germans
killed trying to escape over the wall.
   At the Friederichstrasse crossing point, known as <ORGANIZATION>Checkpoint
Charlie</ORGANIZATION>, renowned cellist <PERSON>Mstislav Rostropovich</PERSON> gave an impromptu
concert <DATE>Saturday</DATE> in front of a section of the wall covered with
graffiti.
   Police said a 24-year-old visitor from <LOCATION>Potsdam</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>,
went into labor on bustling <ORGANIZATION>Wuerttembergische Strasse</ORGANIZATION> and gave
birth to a girl on the sidewalk, to the delight of a surrounding
crowd.
   Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON> of <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> said he would meet with
<ORGANIZATION>Krenz</ORGANIZATION>, whose three weeks in office have brought a whirlwind of
change, to discuss ways of cooperating in the new age.
   However, <ORGANIZATION>Krenz</ORGANIZATION> told <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> to forget any ideas of making the two
nations that rose from the rubble of World War II into a single
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> again.
   East <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>'s Communist authorities built the 14-foot-high
<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall beginning <DATE>Aug. 13, 1961</DATE>, to stem a flow of workers to
the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>. Ironically, it was another flight this year, of more than
200,000 East Germans, that forced them to open it.
   East German leaders lifted travel regulations and pledged
greater democratic freedoms after both the exodus and weeks of
street protests.
</TEXT>
