<DESCRIPT>  GERMANY; HISTORY; BUILDING; DATE; CEREMONY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  East German children used to present flowers every Aug. 13 to the troops who
guarded the Berlin Wall and supposedly protected them from fascism creeping in
from the West.;    Instead of flowers, Chancellor Helmut Kohl declared Monday
that prosecutions await guards in now-united Germany accused of killing nearly
200 would-be escapees from former East Germany.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BERLIN WALL TURNS 30
GUARDS WHO KILLED WILL BE PROSECUTED  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The statement -- on the eve of the 30th anniversary of the erection of the
<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall -- reflects the changes in this country. Berliner Zeitung,
formerly an East German communist newspaper that reported dutifully how
important the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall was as a barrier against fascism, devoted an
eight-page section <DATE>Monday</DATE> to the wall's history and the emotions that
accompanied its opening.;    <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg Gate</ORGANIZATION>'s new role;  The 200-year-old
Brandenburg Gate stood just on the east side of the 100-mile-long wall and
became part of the symbolism of divided <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>. Now it is
refurbished and ready to take on a role as an east-west traffic artery.;   
<DATE>Today</DATE>, <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON>Eberhard Diepgen</PERSON> will lay a wreath at the place where one
of the most heart-wrenching dramas occurred at the wall, in <DATE>1962</DATE>, when
18-year-old <PERSON>Peter Fechter</PERSON> was shot trying to escape. He was left to bleed to
death.;    The <PERSON>Berliner Zeitung</PERSON> on <DATE>Monday</DATE> reprinted the death notice for the
last victim killed at the wall, <PERSON>Chris Gueffroy</PERSON>, who died <DATE>Feb. 2, 1989</DATE>. The
family said in the notice that he had died in a "tragic accident.";    Border
troops face charges;  A popular revolution forced the barricade open <DATE>Nov. 9,
1989.</DATE>;    <PERSON>Erich Honecker</PERSON>, who oversaw construction of the wall in <DATE>1961</DATE> before
he became head of the <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party</ORGANIZATION>, escaped to <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION> in <DATE>March</DATE> and will not
be prosecuted. But several former East German border troops already face
charges, and prosecutors are assembling evidence against other Communist
leaders of <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> who issued the shoot-to-kill orders.  </TEXT>
