<HEAD>Authorities Report Vandalism, Neo-Fascism Spreading in East
Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals and New Year's Eve revelers
extensively damaged <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>'s Brandenburg Gate and neo-fascist
slogans were smeared on monuments in East German cities,
authorities reported <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   Officials said one man died and about 300 people were hurt in
holiday celebrations along the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall, the official ADN news
agency reported. They said many were treated for cuts from
shattered champagne bottles and for broken bones.
   More than 500,000 Germans gathered along the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall to
cheer the arrival of <DATE>1990</DATE>. Hundreds scaled the towering <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg
Gate</ORGANIZATION> and nearby structures.
   The bronze chariot and horses atop the monument were damaged and
some sections will have to be replaced, said <PERSON>Horst Weiss</PERSON> of the
national office for protection of memorials.
   A laurel wreath affixed to a statue of the Greek goddess <ORGANIZATION>Nike</ORGANIZATION>
was stolen, and someone tried to break off an arm, <PERSON>Weiss</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>ADN</ORGANIZATION>.
   East <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> police spokesman <PERSON>Michael Braemer</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>The Associated
Press</ORGANIZATION> the death of a 24-year-old <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> man found in <LOCATION>East
Berlin</LOCATION> was under investigation. Authorities first thought he died
when scaffolding holding up an outdoor projection screen collapsed
under the weight of revelers shortly after <TIME>1 a.m.</TIME> on New Year's.
But <PERSON>Braemer</PERSON> said he may have fallen from a tree along <ORGANIZATION>Unter den
Linden</ORGANIZATION>.
   ADN said neo-Nazi groups smeared slogans on memorials in other
cities and some physical attacks were reported.
   In <LOCATION>Pirna</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Goerlitz</PERSON> near <LOCATION>Dresden</LOCATION>, ``Hitler Lives,'' and ``We
are here _ REP,'' the abbreviation for <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s ultraright
Republican Party, were scrawled on walls and windows, <ORGANIZATION>ADN</ORGANIZATION> said.
   In <PERSON>Goerlitz</PERSON> ``Foreigners Out'' and ``Jews Out'' were painted on
structures and a memorial to those persecuted under the Nazis was
daubed with swastikas, the agency said.
   Anti-communist demonstrators in <LOCATION>Halle</LOCATION> spraypainted ``SED _ No
Thank You'' on memorials, referring to the <ORGANIZATION>East German Communist
Party</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``Skinheads'' and neo-Nazi youths carrying homemade weapons
threatened passers-by in <LOCATION>Erfurt</LOCATION> and two people were hurt
confronting them, <ORGANIZATION>ADN</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The report said some of those arrested said they supported the
Republicans.
   ADN said <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party</ORGANIZATION> groups planned to protest in <LOCATION>East
Berlin</LOCATION> <DATE>this week</DATE> the recent spate of neo-Nazi activity in <LOCATION>East
Germany</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
