<HEAD>News Teams Driven Away With Cattle Prods During Michael Jackson
Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German police drove away Western news teams
with cattle prods as they tried to film East German youths massing
to hear a <PERSON>Michael Jackson</PERSON> concert just across the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall, the
journalists said <DATE>today</DATE>.
   About 4,000 East Germans gathered near the <LOCATION>Brandenburg Gate</LOCATION> on
<DATE>Sunday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>. They came to hear the American rock 'n' roll star
perform about 200 yards away for thousands of others at his concert
in <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION>.
   West German television news teams were on the <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION> side
of the wall and tried to film the crowd.
   But East German security police, waving electronic cattle prods,
drove them away from the scene, said the journalists.
   <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s diplomatic mission protested the incident to the
East German government.
   Witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there was a
large contingent of communist plainclothes security men deployed
among the East German fans. They said a few arrests were made.
   On <DATE>Friday</DATE>, about 2,000 East Germans gathered near the
<LOCATION>Brandenburg Gate</LOCATION> to hear the British rock group <ORGANIZATION>Pink Floyd</ORGANIZATION>, which
performed in <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> on the first night of a three-night
``<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Rock Marathon.''
   East German security police arrested about 40 people during that
concert, witnesses said.
</TEXT>
