<HEAD>Mitterrand Meets East German Leaders; United Germany on Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Romania, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Mitterrand condemning Romanian
leader. Pickup 2nd pvs, `His visit...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President <PERSON>Francois Mitterrand</PERSON> of <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> said
<DATE>today</DATE> that the days of Romanian leader <PERSON>Nicolae Ceausescu</PERSON> are
numbered and called for his replacement.
   ``It is a regime of personal, family power that has no honest
reason to remain,'' <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON> said at a news conference during his
three-day visit to <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>. ``I think that the days of this
regime, in a <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> in full movement, are numbered. But at what
price!''
   In his first condemnation of the bloody suppression of protests
in <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON> ruled out foreign intervention to topple
<PERSON>Ceausescu</PERSON>. He said ``the response has to come from <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>.''
   Mitterrand also met with East German political leaders today to
express the concerns of the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION> about the possibility of German
unification.
   His visit came as West German Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON> told West
German lawmakers that the Germanys plan to strengthen all economic
and political ties.
   But <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> also tried to ease the concerns of European nations
worried about a united <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>, saying the growing closeness of the
two countries can only help the continent.
   Meanwhile, the West German government said <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> would
open <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>'s Brandenburg Gate on <DATE>Friday</DATE>. The gate is a historic
portion of the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall viewed by many as a symbol of German
unity.
   Kohl, East German Premier <PERSON>Hans Modrow</PERSON>, <PERSON>West Berlin Walter
Momper</PERSON>, and <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON>Erhard Krack</PERSON> will participate in the
historic ceremonies, said government spokesman <PERSON>Hans Klein</PERSON>.
   The official East German news agency <ORGANIZATION>ADN</ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON> met
with <PERSON>Modrow</PERSON> and that the ``joint responsibility for balance in
<LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>'' was the main topic.
   Mitterrand and <PERSON>Modrow</PERSON> also discussed the possibility of
expanding ties, while the East German premier expressed interest in
a trade and cooperation agreement with the <ORGANIZATION>European Economic
Community</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>ADN</ORGANIZATION> said.
   It added that <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON> had reacted ``positively'' to the idea
of closer East German ties to the <ORGANIZATION>EEC</ORGANIZATION>.
   But before leaving <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON> said: ``For
the whole of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, it would not be good _ indeed it would be very
dangerous _ to reopen the issue of the existing borders.''
   In an interview with East German television, he also said the
``two paths open for the Germans are the democratic path and the
peaceful path.''
   The possibility of reunification was raised after the
pro-democracy movement recently forced the <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>East
Germany</LOCATION> to oust its hard-line leaders, lift travel restrictions and
open the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall.
   Mitterrand arrived <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, a few hours after Kohl <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>
ended an emotionally charged visit to <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> that brought out
thousands advocating reunification.
   During <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON>'s visit, French and East German officials are
to sign several agreements, including a five-year project for
closer economic and technical cooperation.
   At a state dinner <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> hosted by <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>'s interim
president <PERSON>Manfred Gerlach</PERSON>, a non-Communist, <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON> paid tribute
to the East German pro-democracy movement and said the Germans
should determine their own future.
   But he stressed that ``no country may impose its political
system on another.'' He said closer German ties would result in the
context of a strengthened <ORGANIZATION>European Community</ORGANIZATION> and a general
overcoming of the continent's division. Mitterrand is representing
the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION>EC</ORGANIZATION>, whose rotating presidency <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> holds until <DATE>Dec.
31</DATE>.
   He is also the first head of state from the three western World
War II Allies to visit <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>.
   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> have
ultimate authority over <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>, a result of the postwar occupation
of Hitler's defeated Third <PERSON>Reich</PERSON>.
   While relations between <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> and <PERSON>Mitterrand</PERSON> are close, the
French leader's statements before his trip highlighted traditional
French wariness of a strong <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> at the heart of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
