<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Imelda Marcos</PERSON>' new attorney, trying to repair
the image of the former Philippine first lady, asks that people
compare her with <PERSON>Nancy Reagan</PERSON>.
   ``Suppose <PERSON>Mrs. Reagan</PERSON> were abducted from her home in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
and taken to the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> and charged in the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> with
crimes she allegedly committed in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>,'' the attorney, <PERSON>Gerry
Spence</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE>. ``How do you think <PERSON>Mrs. Reagan</PERSON> would feel?''
   <PERSON>Spence</PERSON> made his remarks after a federal court hearing on the
racketeering indictment that charged <PERSON>Mrs. Marcos</PERSON> and her late
husband, <PERSON>Ferdinand Marcos</PERSON>, with embezzling more than <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY>
from the Philippine treasury to buy art and <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION> real estate.
They also were charged with defrauding banks of <MONEY>$165 million</MONEY> in
loans. Marcos died in exile in <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION> on <DATE>Sept. 28</DATE> at age 72.
   Spence of <ORGANIZATION>Jackson Hole</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Wyo.</LOCATION>, who had represented the family of
<PERSON>Karen Silkwood</PERSON>, was hired by <PERSON>Mrs. Marcos</PERSON> as part of changes in her
defense team that included the dropping of two other attorneys.
</TEXT>
