<HEAD>Protests, Escape Attempt Mark Anniversary of Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with protests in East Germany
and Budapest. Pick up 7th pvs, ``The August...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germans vandalized the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall, an
official called for its removal, and an East German tried to escape
to the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION> on <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, the 28th anniversary of the day construction
began on the infamous barrier.
   Security forces also dispersed about 50 East Germans who tried
to demonstrate in <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION> in front of the West German mission,
which was closed last week after a crowd of East Germans arrived
seeking refuge.
   Witnesses said the demonstrators tried to lay flowers at the
mission gates in an apparent act of solidarity with their
countrymen holed up inside demanding exit visas to the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>. No
protesters were arrested.
   <PERSON>Dorothee Wilms</PERSON>, the West German minister for inter-German
affairs, criticized <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>'s effort ``to build up and perfect
the inhumane barriers'' between East and <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>. Her deputy chief,
<PERSON>Ottfried Hennig</PERSON>, predicted the wall would be taken down by the end
of the century.
   An unidentified assailant hurled a firebomb at the wall near the
Brandenburg Gate early <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, West German police said. The bomb
exploded when it crashed against the wall, but it burned out
without causing serious damage.
   The East German state news agency, ADN, said several masked
assailants from <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> damaged border barriers in the southern
sector of <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>.
   ADN, which did not describe the damage, said a diplomatic
protest would be lodged with <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> authorities.
   Witnesses at the <ORGANIZATION>Checkpoint Charlie</ORGANIZATION> border crossing between East
and <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> reported <DATE>Sunday</DATE> that at least one man attempted to
flee across the heavily guarded crossing just before noon. He was
arrested by East German border guards before reaching Western
territory, the witnesses said.
   In <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>, 200 people gathered at downtown
<LOCATION>Voeroesmarty Square</LOCATION> to protest the wall. The speakers, who included
young East German tourists, called for its demolition.
   Several displayed placards with slogans proclaiming, ``Make
Love, Not Wall,'' and ``We Have No Need of Any Control.'' No
violence was reported during the 40-minute demonstration.
   The <DATE>August</DATE> 13th Society, a human rights organization that
monitors East European refugee affairs, estimates that at least
40,000 East Germans have escaped across the borders with <LOCATION>West
Germany</LOCATION> since the wall was erected.
   Prior to <DATE>1961</DATE>, hundreds of thousands of East Germans fled to the
West, draining the Communist state of many of its top scientists,
artists and intellectuals. The number of escapes surged over the
last few months after <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> began dismantling its border barriers
with <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION>.
   East Germans can usually obtain permission to travel to <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>,
a neighboring Communist ally, and an estimated 1,500 of them have
illegally crossed from there into <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION> this <DATE>summer</DATE>.
   Several hundred East Germans have recently sought refuge at West
German embassies, which has prompted <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> to close its embassy in
<LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> and its mission in <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> defended the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall and said hopes
for its removal are ``illusory.'' Neues Deutschland, the newspaper
of the <ORGANIZATION>East German Communist Party</ORGANIZATION>, said the wall is ``a step
toward peace'' and that it will remain in place to prevent East
Germans from fleeing to the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
