<HEAD>Berlin Revisited: Reagan Wins Cheers Where He Was Once Jeered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>, once lambasted by
angry demonstrators in divided <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>, was hailed <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> as a
returning hero.
   On <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> is to cross into <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION> at the
<LOCATION>Brandenburg Gate</LOCATION>, where he gave a speech in <DATE>1987</DATE> challenging <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION>
to tear down the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall. That visit was marred by
demonstrations by 25,000 people opposed to <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> foreign policy.
   Now that East and <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> are to reunite in <DATE>October</DATE>, the
atmosphere is transformed. On <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the 79-year-old saw only
cheerful faces in his brief contact with the public.
   About 100 Germans and foreign tourists gathered outside the
<ORGANIZATION>Bristol Kempinski Hotel</ORGANIZATION> to see <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> and his wife <PERSON>Nancy</PERSON> leave for
a diplomatic dinner. They applauded and called for autographs.
   The Berliner Morgenpost daily welcomed <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>'s visit with a
headline saying his walk through the Brandenburg Gate will mean
``<PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>'s Dream Fulfilled.''
   <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> and his wife arrived in <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> early in the day to open a
10-day European trip.
   During his <DATE>1987</DATE> visit, <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> voiced skepticism about reforms
started by Soviet President <PERSON>Mikhail S. Gorbachev</PERSON>. He said the one
thing <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION> could do to advance the cause of peace would be to
dismantle the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall.
   ``<PERSON>Mr. Gorbachev</PERSON>, open this gate,'' <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> said. ``<PERSON>Mr. Gorbachev</PERSON>,
tear down this wall.''
   The former Communist rulers of <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> opened the wall in
<DATE>November</DATE> in one of their last, desperate acts to stay in power.
   On <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> will travel about a mile into <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>
to meet with officials there _ now democratically elected.
</TEXT>
