<HEAD>Hot-Air Balloons With Peace Slogans at Brandenburg Gate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two hot-air balloons bearing peace slogans
were anchored <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in front of the <LOCATION>Brandenburg Gate</LOCATION> as a sign
of friendship.
   Dozens of people looked on as a joint French-West German team
began anchoring the mammoth, brightly colored balloons.
   The team had expected officials would turn down their request to
anchor the balloons on <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION> territory, but the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign
Ministry</ORGANIZATION> granted permission, the official ADN news agency said.
   ``We have the luck to experience this new epoch of peace and
understanding,'' said <PERSON>Jean-Marc Culas</PERSON>, the head of the team. ``We
simply wanted to be there and bring our message with the balloons
to everyone.''
   It was yet another sign of relaxed rules along the once-dreaded
<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall, where dozens of souvenir-seekers continue hack away on
the western side gathering souvenirs.
   <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> police said they had taken into custody two
Americans and a <LOCATION>West Berlin</LOCATION> man who had broken out seven sections
of the wall, each measuring 8 feet high by more than 3 feet wide.
   The unidentified men apparently wanted to sell the sections as
souvenirs and had loaded five of them onto a truck before they were
caught, police said. Police said they were cited for theft and
released.
</TEXT>
