<HEAD>Kohl Ends Visit With Appeal for Aid and Patience</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 2 `At the;' graf 9 `Kohl, who;' and graf 13 `Bild,
a' to restore dropped words. Picks up 14th, `Kohl and '</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Romania, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DRESDEN, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON> of <LOCATION>West
Germany</LOCATION> recommended <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> that <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> become stronger
economically before considering reunion with its rich and powerful
neighbor.
   At the end of an emotional visit to the <LOCATION>East</LOCATION>, he also discounted
fears of a ``Fourth <PERSON>Reich</PERSON>,'' an increasingly used term that raises
the specter of <PERSON>Adolf Hitler</PERSON>.
   President <PERSON>Francois Mitterrand</PERSON> of <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, who arrived in <LOCATION>East
Berlin</LOCATION> for a three-day official visit hours after <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> returned to
the West, cautioned against changing borders in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>.
   ``For the whole of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, it would not be good _ indeed it
would be very dangerous _ to reopen the issue of the existing
borders,'' he said.
   Before returning to <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> said ``the economic potential of
the German Democratic Republic must be strengthened'' before
reunification became a possibility. He said he expected a treaty
expanding relations to be completed before <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>'s first
free elections, scheduled for <DATE>May 6</DATE>.
   Mitterrand, in an interview with East German TV before leaving
<LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>, said relations between the two German states have ``very
special characteristics.''
   He was the first head of state or government of the three
western World War II Allies to visit <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION>. Aides said his
trip should not be viewed as recognition of <LOCATION>East Berlin</LOCATION> as the East
German capital, which the <ORGANIZATION>Western Allies</ORGANIZATION> reject.
   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> still have
authority over <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> as a result of postwar occupation of Hitler's
Third <PERSON>Reich</PERSON>.
   Kohl, who spent two days in <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>, said at a final news
conference his government would address the concerns of other
European countries as the two Germanys move closer together.
   ``It's the most natural thing that Germans want to live
together, but we all know it cannot come immediately,'' he said.
   East <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>'s parliament scheduled a session for <DATE>Jan. 11-12</DATE> to
debate a new travel law and legislation to promote joint ventures
with Western companies.
   A draft law providing alternatives to military service for
conscientious objectors also will be on the agenda, the official
news agency <ORGANIZATION>ADN</ORGANIZATION> reported.
   Bild, a West German newspaper, said another passage through the
<LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Wall would be opened <DATE>Friday</DATE> at the historic <ORGANIZATION>Brandenburg
Gate</ORGANIZATION>, a symbol of German unity.
   Kohl and Premier <PERSON>Hans Modrow</PERSON> agreed at their summit <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> that
<LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> woulds open a pedestrian crossing at the gate before
<DATE>Christmas</DATE> and would lift travel restrictions for West Germans on
<ORGANIZATION>Christmas Eve</ORGANIZATION>.
   They also signed several agreements and pledged to negotiate a
treaty bringing them closer together, especially by expanding
economic links.
   In a commentary <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>ADN</ORGANIZATION> said the summit was a success,
but ``anyone who hoped'' <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> would arrive ``with a sack full of
Rhine gold rejoiced too early.''
   Kohl told reporters inter-German issues that could be discussed
soon included improving traffic connections and solving joint
telecommunications and pollution problems.
   ``We will have to work intensively'' on a common German
currency, he said, and acknowledged that as ``one of the most
difficult questions.''
   <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> said the aim of a common currency was to allow West Germans
to buy goods in <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>. East <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> restricts such purchases
because state subsidies make many goods much cheaper than in <LOCATION>West
Germany</LOCATION>, and shortages are feared.
   In a sign of the rapidly increasing economic links, <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>
announced <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> the first joint venture with a West German firm
had been signed. A compact disc manufacturing plant is to be built
by the Pilz company, based outside <LOCATION>Munich</LOCATION>, and the East German
state conglomerate Robotron.
   In <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION>, a working group of both nations on promoting tourism
held its first meeting.
   Kohl said <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> will support reform in <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION> and
``not only talk, but act.'' He pledged, however, to avoid
``destabilization,'' an apparent reference to the power vacuum
created by the collapse of <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party</ORGANIZATION> control over the past
two months.
   Addressing the concerns of neighboring countries, <PERSON>Kohl</PERSON> said:
``Fears based in the past are understandable, but there is nothing
to be feared from the future. It's absurd to talk about a Fourth
<PERSON>Reich</PERSON>.''
</TEXT>
